ce:section.ce:para:
Carbon polymer quantum dots are generally regarded as nontoxic, harmless and stable. They have been possibly absorbed, transported and distributed by plants, which could affect the growth of plants. In addition, the nanoparticles have excellent optical properties, which improve the probability of high-resolution imaging of plants. Sesame is an annual, high-temperature preferred plant. It could be suitable for sowing in late May and early June. In this work, sesame was collected as a model plant, and the effective absorption of CPDs was studied. Sesame seeds of similar size and plumpness were selected and immersed in NaClO solution for 10 min, then cultured in the presence of CPDs solution at different concentrations (0.02, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.4 mg/ mL), and distilled water was used as the control group. The experiments were performed at 30 °C for 7 days, sesame seedlings were analyzed. Sesame seeds at different concentrations were germinated, the results supported that both CPDs and pure water cultured sesame seeds could germinate. But the encapsulation of nanoparticles would significantly speed up the growth rate. It is estimated that CPDs have good water permeability, which would be helpful to the adsorption efficiency of seeds. As shown in Fig. 5
                        , there were sharp difference between CPDs-treated group and control group. CPDs can promote sesame germination in the concentration range of 0–0.4 mg/ mL, but the threshold value was measured to be 0.2 mg/ mL, and the growth tendency effect was partially controlled at the concentration higher than 0.2. In order to further study the dose effect of CPDs, we further evaluated biomass of sesame seedlings (Fig. 6
                        ). Compared with the control group, there were significant changes in each group (P ≤ 0.01). Fig. 6(a) and (b) indicated that the roots of sesame seedlings possessed growing trend with the increase of nanoparticles, the stem length was the largest in 0.2 mg/ mL CPDs solution. In order to understand the mechanism of biomass increase of sesame seedlings cultured in CPDs, the fresh weight and dry weight in each group were measured before and after drying at 110 °C for 3 h. Fig. 6(c) shows fresh weight of sesame seedlings treated with different concentration of CPDs. Compared with the control group, the fresh weight of sesame seedlings treated with 0.2 mg/ml CPDs was significantly increased. Fig. 6(d) showed the water content of sesame seedlings treated with different concentrations of CPDs. It can be seen that the moisture content of sesame seedlings in the presence of CPDs was higher than that of control group. When CPDs concentration was used in the range of 0–0.2 mg/ mL, the moisture content was increased gradually and the maximum value could reach at 0.2 mg/ mL. The above data indicated that CPDs could assist to transport active species in plant growth, therefore rapidly increase plant water content and promote seed germination. However, when the concentration was overloaded (>0.2 mg/ mL), the cell dehydration will occur due to the imbalance of the concentration inside and outside of the cell, thus slowing down the growth rate of the plant.
